## 2. Scope and our privacy-by-design approach

The App is designed so that a person’s fitness and biometric data is stored and processed on the server in encrypted form and remains visible only to that person.
The two categories of “actors” that ever have access to your data are:

- **You, the user** – the only human who can view the raw data and results.
- **Automated processing components** – the algorithms running on the server and, only if you opt in, an AI/LLM model that analyse your data to produce insights.

No other human user of the App, and no operator of this instance, can view your decrypted fitness or biometric data in the ordinary course of operation.
Each user's data is held in its own isolated per-user database.
This principle of **data protection by design and by default (Article 25 GDPR)** underpins the whole policy below.

## 3. What data we process

### 3.1 Data you provide or generate

Depending on the features you use, the App may process:

- **Biometric and health data** such as heart rate, weight, heart-rate and power zones, and other fitness metrics you record or connect.
  This is “special-category data” under Article 9 GDPR and receives heightened protection.
- **Activity and derived data** such as workouts, training-load metrics (CTL/ATL/TSB), trends, goals, and insights calculated from your metrics.
- **Account and configuration data** such as your username, display name, chosen settings, and preferences.

### 3.2 Technical data

- **Device and app data** such as app version and diagnostic/error logs, used to keep the App working and secure.

**Note on special-category data:** biometric data used to analyse your physical condition and health metrics falls within Article 9 GDPR.
We only process it on the lawful bases set out in Section 5 and with the safeguards described in this policy.

## 4. How your data is processed and stored

### 4.1 Server-side, encrypted storage

Your fitness and biometric data is stored on the server{% if hosting_provider %}, hosted with {{ hosting_provider }},{% endif %} in **{{ encryption_description or "encrypted form [describe the at-rest encryption and key management for this instance]" }}**, in a per-user database that logically isolates it from other users.
The data is transmitted between your device and the server over an encrypted connection (TLS).
It is accessible only to you and to the App’s automated processing components; it is not exposed to other users or, in the ordinary course of operation, to the instance operator.

### 4.2 Automated algorithmic processing

Algorithms running on the server process your data to calculate metrics, detect trends, and generate insights.
This processing runs automatically and produces results that only you can see.
It does not involve any human reviewer.

### 4.3 Optional AI / LLM analysis

**AI analysis is optional and off by default.**
If — and only if — you enable an AI analysis feature, relevant data is sent to a large language model (“LLM”) to produce a natural-language analysis of your fitness data.

- **You choose the provider and model.**
  The LLM provider and specific model are configurable.
  Before analysis runs, the App clearly shows you which provider and which model will process your data, so you can make an informed choice.
- **Transparency at the point of use.**
  The active provider and model name are displayed in the AI settings screen and alongside each analysis result.
- **What is sent.**
  Only the data necessary for the requested analysis is transmitted — the specific metrics and time range relevant to the insight.
- **Your ability to stop.**
  You can disable AI analysis at any time, after which no further data is sent to any LLM provider.

**Important:** when you enable AI analysis, the data you submit is transmitted to and processed by the third-party AI provider you selected, under that provider’s own terms and privacy policy.
Their handling of your data (including whether it is used for model training, how long it is retained, and where it is processed) is governed by them.
See Section 8 for the providers available on this instance.

## 5. Lawful bases for processing

Under the GDPR we must have a lawful basis for each processing activity. Ours are:

| Processing activity | Lawful basis (Art. 6) | Special-category condition (Art. 9) |
|---|---|---|
| Core server-side processing of your fitness/biometric data to provide the App | Art. 6(1)(b) – performance of a contract with you | Art. 9(2)(a) – your explicit consent |
| Optional AI/LLM analysis of your data | Art. 6(1)(a) – consent | Art. 9(2)(a) – your explicit consent, given per feature |
| Security, diagnostics, and app stability | Art. 6(1)(f) – legitimate interests | N/A (no health data used for this purpose) |
| Compliance with legal obligations | Art. 6(1)(c) – legal obligation | As applicable |

**Explicit consent for biometric data.**
Because biometric health data is special-category data, we rely on your explicit consent.
Consent is requested separately and clearly, is not bundled with other terms, and can be **withdrawn at any time** without affecting the lawfulness of processing carried out before withdrawal.
Withdrawing consent to AI analysis stops that feature; withdrawing consent to core processing means the App can no longer function and you may export or delete your data.

## 6. Who can access your data

- **You** – full access to your own data and insights.
- **Automated processing** – algorithms and, if enabled, your chosen LLM, acting on your data to generate results only you see.
- **No other users** – the App does not expose your data to any other user.
- **The instance operator** – cannot access your decrypted fitness/biometric data in the normal course of operation, even though it is stored on the server.
  Data is held per-user and, where configured, encrypted at rest.
- **Third-party AI providers** – only the provider/model you select, only when you enable AI analysis, and only for the data sent for that analysis.

## 7. Automated decision-making

The App uses algorithms and optional AI to generate insights and suggestions about your fitness.
These are informational and do not produce legal or similarly significant effects on you within the meaning of **Article 22 GDPR**.
They are decision-support tools, not automated decisions that determine your rights or obligations.

